On 4/30/10 5:16 AM, sriram_varahan1 wrote:
&gt; Hello,
&gt;
&gt;       Thanks a lot for the reply!
&gt;
&gt;&gt; That&#39;s not accurate. What part of the release notes gave you that
&gt;&gt; impression? We&#39;ll correct it.
&gt;
&gt; Regarding my interpretation of Heritrix 3 being able to handle updates out of the box, I inferred that from some document which said &quot;Heritrix now assumes a job will be launched multiple times&quot;.
&gt; So I thought it may be updating it.
&gt;
&gt;&gt; If you have the most aggressive duplication-reduction settings (sending
&gt;&gt; &quot;If-Modified&quot;/&quot;If-None-Match&quot; headers and respecting not-changed
&gt;&gt; responses from servers), and Heritrix is able to skip fetching an
&gt;&gt; unchanged page entirely, it won&#39;t even have the outlinks to continue the
&gt;&gt; current crawl. (We don&#39;t carry the discovered links forward in the URI
&gt;&gt; history info.)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; So, if you want use those settings, it&#39;s up to you to feed the crawler
&gt;&gt; those URIs from the earlier crawl(s) you want it to re-check.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I wrote a script which fetched all the crawled URI&#39;s and updated the seeds.txt with those URI&#39;s. It updated the mirror but it also crawled the external domains.
&gt;
&gt; So on looking into the surts.dump I found the external URI&#39;s were also considered.
&gt;
&gt; I figured out that the seeds.txt is used to construct the surts.dump and hence it fetches the external URI&#39;s also.
&gt;
&gt; Is there any other way of supplying URI&#39;s to Heritrix apart from the seeds.txt.

Well, on the SurtPrefixedDecideRule, you can set the 
&#39;seedsAsSurtPrefixes&#39; setting to &#39;false&#39; -- and then it won&#39;t use the 
seeds URIs to define the scope.

Note that your &#39;seeds&#39; text may still include &#39;+&#39; and &#39;-&#39; SURT 
directives, which will still be noted by  SurtPrefixedDecideRule with 
ACCEPT(+) or REJECT(-) decisions respectively, even if 
seedsAsSurtPrefixes is false.

But also, you can feed non-seed URIs to a crawl by dropping a file of 
them into the &#39;action&#39; directory, in a format similar to the &#39;.recovery&#39; 
log format (which is a 2-character directive, a space, then the URI, 
with optional other info after the URI)). See here for more details on 
the kinds of dynamic additions possible via this mechanism:

https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/Action+Directory

To add URIs, a file of type &#39;.schedule&#39; or &#39;.force&#39; would be 
appropriate. Note that the two-character leading directive can be 
anything for these file types. (The exact directive matters when 
providing a &#39;.recovery&#39; file type.)

- Gordon @ IA


